<TITLE> India's Congress criticises left for shunning poor </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Apr 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The following is a snapshot of recent developments in India's general election campaign. The sources are mentioned in brackets. Sonia Gandhi, the Congress party chief, criticised the ruling communists of West Bengal for not doing enough for the rural poor, a move that could further deteriorate relations between the Congress and its former allies. Addressing an election rally, Gandhi, said the left parties would be defeated in the general election and there was no democracy in the state. (HINDUSTAN TIMES) M. Karunanidhi, chief minister of Tamil Nadu, ended a fast for the rights of Tamil civilians of Sri Lanka, after its government called off combat operations against Tamil rebels. The Tamil cause is a major election issue in the state, and all parties are trying to woo voters, who are sympathetic towards the Tamils in Sri Lanka. (THE TIMES OF INDIA) The Supreme Court ordered an investigation into the role played by Narendra Modi, the chief minister of Gujarat, during a religious riot in 2002. Modi, has been accused of turning a blind eye to the communal riots, in which more than 2,500 people, mostly Muslims, were killed in the Bharatiya Janata Party-ruled state. If implicated soon, it could hurt the BJP and affect its chances of winning in the election. (THE TIMES OF INDIA) WHAT THE NEWSPAPERS SAY: The statement by communists, calling for a prime minister only from the lower house of parliament, makes very little sense after supporting Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, who is from the upper house for four years. "The left must realise that this tone and tenor is neither increasing the probability that the Congress will support a post-poll CPM-led formation, the left's ostensible goal, nor will it help to convince voters
